SIMPLE: proportion
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proportion
<hw>Pro*por"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>proportio</ets>; <ets>pro</ets> before + <ets>portio</ets> part or
share. See <er>Portion</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The relation or adaptation of one portion to
another, or to the whole, as respect magnitude, quantity, or degree;
comparative relation; ratio; <as>as, the <ex>proportion</ex> of the
parts of a building, or of the body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The image of Christ, made after his own <qex>proportion</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ridley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Formed in the best <qex>proportions</qex> of her sex.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Documents are authentic and facts are true precisely in
<qex>proportion</qex> to the support which they afford to his
theory.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Harmonic relation between parts, or between
different things of the same kind; symmetrical arrangement or
adjustment; symmetry; <as>as, to be out of
<ex>proportion</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Let us prophesy according to the
<xex>proportion</xex> of faith.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Rom. xii.
6.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The portion one receives when a whole is distributed
by a rule or principle; equal or proper share; lot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let the women . . . do the same things in their
<qex>proportions</qex> and capacities.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A part considered comparatively; a share.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The equality or
similarity of ratios, especially of geometrical ratios; or a relation
among quantities such that the quotient of the first divided by the
second is equal to that of the third divided by the fourth; -- called
also <altname>geometrical proportion</altname>, in distinction from
<xex>arithmetical proportion</xex>, or that in which the difference of
the first and second is equal to the difference of the third and
fourth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Proportion</xex> in the mathematical sense differs
from <xex>ratio</xex>. <xex>Ratio</xex> is the relation of two
quantities of the same kind, as the ratio of 5 to 10, or the ratio of 8
to 16. <xex>Proportion</xex> is the sameness or likeness of two such
relations. Thus, 5 to 10 as 8 to 16; that is, 5 bears the same relation
to 10 as 8 does to 16. Hence, such numbers are said to be in
<xex>proportion</xex>. <xex>Proportion</xex> is expressed by symbols
thus:⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><mathex>a:b::c:d</mathex>, or <mathex>a:b = c:d</mathex>, or
<mathex><fract>a/b</fract> = <fract>c/d</fract></mathex>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The rule of three, in arithmetic, in which the
three given terms, together with the one sought, are
proportional.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Continued proportion</b></col>, <col><b>Inverse
proportion</b></col>, etc.</mcol> <cd>See under <er>Continued</er>,
<er>Inverse</er>, etc.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Harmonical
proportion</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Musical
proportion</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a relation of three or four quantities,
such that the first is to the last as the difference between the first
two is to the difference between the last two; thus, 2, 3, 6, are in
harmonical proportion; for 2 is to 6 as 1 to 3. Thus, 24, 16, 12, 9, are
harmonical, for <mathex>24:9::8:3</mathex>.</cd> -- <col><b>In
proportion</b></col>, <cd>according as; to the degree that.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>In proportion</xex> as they are metaphysically true, they
are morally and politically false.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Burke.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proportion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Proportion
<hw>Pro*por"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Proportioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Proportioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>proportionner</ets>. Cf. <er>Proportionate</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To adjust in a suitable
proportion, as one thing or one part to another; <as>as, to
<ex>proportion</ex> the size of a building to its height; to
<ex>proportion</ex> our expenditures to our income.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the loss of an object we do not <qex>proportion</qex> our grief
to the real value . . . but to the value our fancies set upon it.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form with symmetry or suitableness, as the parts
of the body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature had <qex>proportioned</qex> her without any fault.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To divide into equal or just shares; to
apportion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proportionable</ent>⟦br⟧
